00:15:14.120 --> 00:15:15.840
compounds or biologics.

255
00:15:18.160 --> 00:15:21.670
Basically anybody is eligible to apply, researchers in academia,

256
00:15:22.040 --> 00:15:23.160
government, industry.

257
00:15:24.320 --> 00:15:27.420
And there's kind of three main stages.

258
00:15:27.580 --> 00:15:31.120
One would be the discovery stage. If you're still doing target

259
00:15:31.140 --> 00:15:34.840
validation, hit to lead screening, that would be

260
00:15:34.860 --> 00:15:38.520
discovery. The development program is once there's a lead

261
00:15:38.560 --> 00:15:42.500
identified and you're going up through

262
00:15:42.520 --> 00:15:45.700
the IND-enabling activities to IND, that's where you would apply.

263
00:15:46.190 --> 00:15:48.960
And then there's also a clinical arm.

264
00:15:49.040 --> 00:15:51.600
If you have IND and you're looking for

265
00:15:54.440 --> 00:15:57.320
resources for clinical trials, we have the NCI

266
00:15:58.960 --> 00:16:01.820
networks for clinical trials, and so you could apply there.

267
00:16:02.620 --> 00:16:06.300
So, this is a competitive program that you have to

268
00:16:06.310 --> 00:16:09.980
apply to. Again, it's not a grant, but rather a resource

269
00:16:09.989 --> 00:16:13.890
program. And everything is really advanced in a

270
00:16:13.900 --> 00:16:17.510
milestone-driven manner, so projects will go through

271
00:16:17.860 --> 00:16:20.920
different phases of whether they continue or not.

272
00:16:22.500 --> 00:16:26.200
And currently, submission deadlines are just on an ad hoc

273
00:16:26.240 --> 00:16:30.179
basis. And I put the contact information for

274
00:16:30.220 --> 00:16:34.049
program managers if you're interested in learning more or

275
00:16:34.080 --> 00:16:35.840
when those next deadlines will be.

276
00:16:38.420 --> 00:16:42.080
This is just to emphasize that there are flexible entry

277
00:16:42.120 --> 00:16:45.740
points for the next pipeline, and they can advance

278
00:16:46.260 --> 00:16:50.160
all the way through from discovery to the more development stage

279
00:16:50.920 --> 00:16:53.980
based on go, no go criteria, and

280
00:16:55.240 --> 00:16:58.600
can eventually get to clinical trials if you go through the entire

281
00:16:58.640 --> 00:16:59.240
pipeline.

282
00:17:01.720 --> 00:17:05.560
Just to compare, since I've introduced a couple different programs,

283
00:17:05.661 --> 00:17:08.921
the next program, which I just talked about,

284
00:17:09.421 --> 00:17:10.860
is a real full

285
00:17:12.200 --> 00:17:15.421
program for drug discovery, development, and clinical

286
00:17:15.980 --> 00:17:19.840
evaluation. These are large projects, milestone driven.

287
00:17:20.980 --> 00:17:23.020
You need to apply and

288
00:17:24.401 --> 00:17:27.800
get peer reviewed by NCI for

289
00:17:28.220 --> 00:17:32.020
this resource. It is resources, not grant money that's given

290
00:17:32.080 --> 00:17:32.340
out.

291
00:17:33.400 --> 00:17:37.100
And anything that's intellectual property brought into the program is

292
00:17:37.120 --> 00:17:38.720
retained by the investigators.

293
00:17:39.620 --> 00:17:43.580
Stepping Stones, on the other hand, it's really focused on our active grant

294
00:17:43.660 --> 00:17:45.780
portfolio and NCI grantees.

295
00:17:47.020 --> 00:17:50.700
We have limited this to a small molecule focus at this

296
00:17:50.760 --> 00:17:54.220
time, and really it's limited gap-filling studies that may make you more

297
00:17:54.240 --> 00:17:56.800
competitive for things like NExT or SBIR.

298
00:17:57.780 --> 00:18:01.400
These are prioritized within a program

299
00:18:01.740 --> 00:18:05.200
based on feasibility and need, and

300
00:18:05.700 --> 00:18:09.360
just like NExT, it provides resources, not money for the

301
00:18:09.460 --> 00:18:09.960
studies.

302
00:18:10.980 --> 00:18:13.840
But you also retain any IP brought into the program.

303
00:18:14.900 --> 00:18:16.720
And with that, I'll turn it over to Sundar.

304
00:18:25.650 --> 00:18:28.050
Good afternoon, everyone. Thank you for attending this session.

305
00:18:28.610 --> 00:18:32.230
I'll shift gears a little bit and talk about funding opportunities

306
00:18:32.650 --> 00:18:36.630
for academic researchers, as well as companies who

307
00:18:37.050 --> 00:18:40.850
do apply for some of the grant opportunities at NCI,

308
00:18:41.190 --> 00:18:45.150
as well as some grant writing strategies for new and

309
00:18:45.250 --> 00:18:46.630
early-stage investigators.

310
00:18:48.010 --> 00:18:50.550
I have no financial relationships to disclose.

311
00:18:51.370 --> 00:18:55.290
So as an overview, I'll provide the different types of funding

312
00:18:55.330 --> 00:18:57.180
mechanisms NCI supports,

313
00:18:58.090 --> 00:19:02.050
and the ways to identify funding opportunities, connecting with a program officer

314
00:19:02.090 --> 00:19:03.130
or a program director

315
00:19:04.130 --> 00:19:07.930
in writing better grants, as well as general guidance and useful

316
00:19:08.010 --> 00:19:09.770
tips for new investigators.

317
00:19:10.850 --> 00:19:14.590
So this table kind of has some of the

318
00:19:14.610 --> 00:19:18.320
major mechanisms we fund through my branch as well as through NCI.

319
00:19:18.810 --> 00:19:21.410
The R01 is usually the largest

320
00:19:23.790 --> 00:19:27.370
fraction of the grants we fund. About 60% of NCI-funded grants

321
00:19:27.790 --> 00:19:31.670
fall into this category. These are projects which are large projects

322
00:19:31.730 --> 00:19:33.890
where you need a lot of preliminary data.

323
00:19:33.930 --> 00:19:36.530
You can apply for grants up to five years.

324
00:19:37.150 --> 00:19:40.850
The modular grants are equal to about $250,000 in

325
00:19:40.890 --> 00:19:44.350
direct costs per year. If you're writing something higher,

326
00:19:44.910 --> 00:19:48.690
it would be more than $250,000 a year, and they are called non-modular, and there's

327
00:19:48.750 --> 00:19:51.370
usually an administrative cut for both of them.

328
00:19:52.070 --> 00:19:55.050
And the key features of these

329
00:19:56.570 --> 00:19:59.590
grants are you need to have decent preliminary data.

330
00:19:59.630 --> 00:20:03.150
The R21 are smaller in scope, and you are looking at exploratory

331
00:20:03.210 --> 00:20:06.410
research as well as data collection, and they are much smaller,

332
00:20:07.150 --> 00:20:11.070
budget-wise, they are smaller. And R03s are even smaller, where you

333
00:20:11.110 --> 00:20:14.510
get $100,000, $50,000 a year, and where your

334
00:20:14.750 --> 00:20:18.570
primary focus is to collect data so that you can apply for an R01

335
00:20:18.650 --> 00:20:18.990
later.

336
00:20:19.810 --> 00:20:23.310
R15 grants are for specific institutions which

337
00:20:23.670 --> 00:20:27.090
need resources where they can improve their research

338
00:20:27.150 --> 00:20:30.190
environment as well as research of training of

339
00:20:30.830 --> 00:20:32.890
students in their respective institutions.

340
00:20:33.299 --> 00:20:37.179
There are other examples which we can go further later, but you can always

341
00:20:37.210 --> 00:20:40.810
look them up at the NIH website. We have K99, which

342
00:20:40.930 --> 00:20:44.030
are training grants. P01s are much larger than

343
00:20:44.530 --> 00:20:48.390
R01s, where a group of investigators get together and write a program project

344
00:20:48.450 --> 00:20:51.990
grant. And R33 is more like milestone-driven

345
00:20:52.090 --> 00:20:53.830
R21/R33 grants.

346
00:20:55.950 --> 00:20:59.870
So the funding opportunities usually fall into three major categories.

347
00:20:59.930 --> 00:21:02.970
The parent announcements are investigator-initiated

348
00:21:04.170 --> 00:21:07.910
grants where pretty much NIH has a single announcement

349
00:21:07.990 --> 00:21:11.890
where you have a great idea, you write an application, whether it's an R21

350
00:21:11.910 --> 00:21:14.790
or an R03 or an R01. You write.

351
00:21:15.890 --> 00:21:19.270
It can be on any topic as long as it is within the

352
00:21:19.690 --> 00:21:22.890
mission of NIH. And there's no money set aside.

353
00:21:22.950 --> 00:21:26.330
It's based on amount of money. Each institute

354
00:21:26.850 --> 00:21:30.390
has its own budget, and it's based on the amount of money they allocate

355
00:21:30.490 --> 00:21:34.390
for these parent announcements. And these are

356
00:21:34.430 --> 00:21:38.080
reviewed by standing study sections run by the Center for Scientific

357
00:21:38.150 --> 00:21:41.990
Review. And the award is usually based on scientific

358
00:21:42.110 --> 00:21:46.070
merit as well as NIH, as well as IC priorities.

359
00:21:47.210 --> 00:21:49.070
Then the request for applications are

360
00:21:49.970 --> 00:21:53.850
contrasts on the right side here is like these are NIH or IC-requested

361
00:21:53.890 --> 00:21:57.650
research where they define an area, and these are

362
00:21:57.690 --> 00:22:00.450
reviewed by special review panels, and there's set aside money.

363
00:22:00.530 --> 00:22:04.070
So they set aside anywhere from 5 million to 200 million, depending on

364
00:22:04.470 --> 00:22:06.110
the scope of the whole

365
00:22:06.310 --> 00:22:09.130
announcement, and

366
00:22:09.210 --> 00:22:12.850
they will have a set up, a special emphasis

367
00:22:12.930 --> 00:22:16.750
panel, and they will award based on the amount

368
00:22:16.810 --> 00:22:20.490
of money available for the RFA, as well as scientific merit, as well as

369
00:22:20.590 --> 00:22:23.930
IC priorities. The center one here is like

370
00:22:24.230 --> 00:22:28.010
program announcements. These are often broadly defined

371
00:22:28.070 --> 00:22:31.750
areas. Once again, awards are based on scientific merit,

372
00:22:32.250 --> 00:22:35.230
and sometimes they have special reviews.

373
00:22:35.730 --> 00:22:39.710
But NCI is moving away from the center model,

374
00:22:39.790 --> 00:22:40.670
where we are going to have

375
00:22:41.610 --> 00:22:43.110
highlighted topics because

376
00:22:43.149 --> 00:22:46.750
in order to

377
00:22:46.850 --> 00:22:50.630
streamline the process, we are going to have highlighted topics which are much

378
00:22:50.690 --> 00:22:54.290
more nimble, and they can be released within a few months so that

379
00:22:54.830 --> 00:22:58.310
PIs can actually focus on research which are highlighted in

380
00:22:58.670 --> 00:23:00.990
specific areas. And you will hear more about these

381
00:23:02.370 --> 00:23:03.670
later as the

382
00:23:04.510 --> 00:23:08.470
fiscal year moves on. And one of my colleagues, Jiang Xie, he's going to

383
00:23:08.510 --> 00:23:08.650
be

384
00:23:09.790 --> 00:23:13.710
in the NCI booth on Monday 21st, and he would be able to

385
00:23:13.770 --> 00:23:15.910
give you some information. I think he's

386
00:23:16.770 --> 00:23:19.050
going to be there from 1:30 to 2:30 PM.

387
00:23:19.430 --> 00:23:19.570
So

388
00:23:20.430 --> 00:23:24.290
you can always come to the NCI booth to get additional information on highlighted

389
00:23:24.330 --> 00:23:24.810
topics.

390
00:23:26.470 --> 00:23:28.670
So how do you identify funding opportunities?

391
00:23:28.790 --> 00:23:29.390
Most of you can

392
00:23:30.310 --> 00:23:33.990
know this already. I think it's a matter of going to the NIH

393
00:23:34.000 --> 00:23:37.310
website, and you can look for specific funding

394
00:23:37.390 --> 00:23:38.190
opportunities.

395
00:23:39.510 --> 00:23:43.270
And you can also, depending on the funding opportunities, you can get

396
00:23:43.320 --> 00:23:47.130
additional information about the funding opportunities using

397
00:23:47.530 --> 00:23:51.340
the information on the scientific contact listed at the end of the funding

398
00:23:51.410 --> 00:23:55.300
opportunity. So usually pretty much most funding opportunities have a

399
00:23:55.330 --> 00:23:59.270
scientific research contact who will provide you some additional

400
00:23:59.310 --> 00:24:00.570
information on specific

401
00:24:02.550 --> 00:24:05.790
criteria being asked for each funding

402
00:24:05.870 --> 00:24:06.690
opportunities.

403
00:24:10.190 --> 00:24:10.330
So

404
00:24:12.490 --> 00:24:16.470
one of the important resources one can find at NIH as well

405
00:24:16.510 --> 00:24:19.990
as at every institute is our program

406
00:24:20.030 --> 00:24:20.630
officials.

407
00:24:21.710 --> 00:24:25.646
You can find them at, as I told earlier inIn

408
00:24:25.706 --> 00:24:29.206
the funding opportunity itself, or you can find a matchmaker tool, which

409
00:24:30.206 --> 00:24:32.006
you can find it in the NIH website.

410
00:24:33.026 --> 00:24:36.966
You can email this funding of a program official

411
00:24:36.986 --> 00:24:38.116
and get some information,

412
00:24:40.446 --> 00:24:44.426
and set up a call so that you could get some additional information about the

413
00:24:44.446 --> 00:24:48.286
funding opportunities. And most of the time, I highly recommend you to

414
00:24:48.926 --> 00:24:49.346
email

415
00:24:51.146 --> 00:24:55.006
your specific aims to a program official so that they can look at

416
00:24:55.066 --> 00:24:57.106
it and provide you some

417
00:24:58.406 --> 00:25:01.906
useful guidance. These are important resources within NIH.

418
00:25:01.966 --> 00:25:04.026
And why do you want to contact them?

419
00:25:04.086 --> 00:25:07.686
Because program officials listen to more than hundreds of

420
00:25:08.466 --> 00:25:12.166
reviews every year, so they know what study sections are looking

421
00:25:12.266 --> 00:25:12.726
for. They

422
00:25:14.126 --> 00:25:17.766
can look at your specific aim and provide information and guidance on whether it is

423
00:25:17.806 --> 00:25:21.706
feasible for an R21 versus R01. We always find

424
00:25:21.746 --> 00:25:25.566
PIs writing a huge R01 but asking for two

425
00:25:26.166 --> 00:25:30.106
years of funding. Sometimes it's the other way around, where you need to have

426
00:25:30.526 --> 00:25:34.316
more preliminary data for an R01 compared to an R21.

427
00:25:35.206 --> 00:25:38.266
Now, once you have a good idea, when do you want to contact them?

428
00:25:38.286 --> 00:25:39.766
When you have a good idea, you can always

429
00:25:41.946 --> 00:25:45.566
email a program officer and ask them whether it is feasible

430
00:25:46.006 --> 00:25:47.306
for a specific mechanism.

431
00:25:48.166 --> 00:25:51.406
And it's okay to write, ask program

432
00:25:51.466 --> 00:25:54.946
official, contact them before you write an

433
00:25:55.626 --> 00:25:58.046
application. But you need to have some idea there.

434
00:25:58.706 --> 00:26:02.266
Then of course, program officers are the major point of contact

435
00:26:02.406 --> 00:26:04.906
after your grant application is reviewed.

436
00:26:04.986 --> 00:26:08.586
They review the summary statement, and they can provide

437
00:26:08.606 --> 00:26:12.586
guidance on how to improve the next submission if it is not going to

438
00:26:12.626 --> 00:26:14.286
be funded based on the scores.

439
00:26:15.986 --> 00:26:19.686
So you can go to the NIH website, you can find the matchmaker

440
00:26:19.766 --> 00:26:23.646
tool. It's basically, you cut and paste your abstract, and it

441
00:26:23.726 --> 00:26:27.586
will find the program officials who kind of manage such

442
00:26:27.666 --> 00:26:31.346
grants. For example, if your research is on the basic aspects of

443
00:26:31.446 --> 00:26:35.206
cancer, cancer biology and so forth, it will most

444
00:26:35.225 --> 00:26:38.566
probably pick a program official from the Division of Cancer Biology.

445
00:26:38.626 --> 00:26:42.426
If it is more translational or preclinical therapeutics, it

446
00:26:42.466 --> 00:26:46.366
will pick somebody in my branch or in our division who

447
00:26:46.966 --> 00:26:50.566
focus on biomarkers, as well as therapeutics, as well as

448
00:26:50.586 --> 00:26:53.846
clinical development projects.

449
00:26:55.966 --> 00:26:59.926
So this slide gives

450
00:26:59.966 --> 00:27:02.966
you some basic idea on general grant writing

451
00:27:03.086 --> 00:27:06.986
strategies. So basically, you need to have a strong premise and a

452
00:27:07.106 --> 00:27:10.746
scientific rationale for writing a successful application.

453
00:27:10.806 --> 00:27:14.726
You want to emphasize on the cancer subtypes, types of cancer you're

454
00:27:14.766 --> 00:27:18.446
working on. You want to have a molecular basis for studying a specific

455
00:27:18.526 --> 00:27:22.496
target. You just can't pick a target and say you're going to work on five

456
00:27:22.546 --> 00:27:26.506
different cancers. And choice of models is very important because

457
00:27:26.546 --> 00:27:29.286
there is a new emphasis at the

458
00:27:30.446 --> 00:27:34.326
NIH level where you want to have clinically relevant models to

459
00:27:34.386 --> 00:27:37.746
work upon. Just because you have a mouse model doesn't mean you have to use it.

460
00:27:37.966 --> 00:27:40.506
If there are better models out there, like organoids or

461
00:27:41.326 --> 00:27:45.226
patient-derived models, it's always better to use

462
00:27:45.266 --> 00:27:47.846
them. And always it's a good idea to have a

463
00:27:47.946 --> 00:27:51.746
statistician look at your grant so that you are

464
00:27:53.286 --> 00:27:55.226
having the right power calculations.

465
00:27:55.946 --> 00:27:59.926
And you should always have a thoughtful discussion on pitfalls, as

466
00:27:59.946 --> 00:28:01.786
well as alternative sections in your grant.

467
00:28:01.846 --> 00:28:02.546
So what if

468
00:28:04.106 --> 00:28:07.006
research experimental approach is not going to work?

469
00:28:07.106 --> 00:28:10.786
What are the alternatives you're going to do, and what are the potential

470
00:28:10.866 --> 00:28:12.286
weaknesses in your approach?

471
00:28:13.586 --> 00:28:15.706
And a lot of

472
00:28:16.946 --> 00:28:20.266
PIs kind of confuse innovation to high level

473
00:28:20.586 --> 00:28:24.186
'omics analysis. You should always have a

474
00:28:25.746 --> 00:28:29.726
clear analysis plan if you are proposing a

475
00:28:30.966 --> 00:28:34.086
lot of 'omics type research in your application.

476
00:28:34.146 --> 00:28:34.966
So you want to have

477
00:28:37.286 --> 00:28:38.326
data analysis

478
00:28:39.326 --> 00:28:40.586
descriptions as well as

479
00:28:41.566 --> 00:28:44.426
information on how the data will be used.

480
00:28:44.946 --> 00:28:48.826
And it's always a good idea to provide a timeline so that reviewers can look

481
00:28:48.886 --> 00:28:52.826
at your application, see that you have done a good faith attempt

482
00:28:52.866 --> 00:28:56.846
to see how each aim is going to be done over a period of five years or two

483
00:28:56.906 --> 00:28:57.186
years.

484
00:28:58.866 --> 00:29:02.746
For new applicants, it's always a good idea to contact the program official earlier

485
00:29:02.826 --> 00:29:06.426
in the process. Seek input from senior colleagues

486
00:29:06.706 --> 00:29:09.766
within your institution, because pretty much most institutions have

487
00:29:10.726 --> 00:29:13.306
ways for junior faculty to contact and

488
00:29:14.966 --> 00:29:17.486
get some help from writing better grants.

489
00:29:17.506 --> 00:29:20.566
And it's always a good idea to write one application per review cycle.

490
00:29:20.676 --> 00:29:21.126
As we see,

491
00:29:22.026 --> 00:29:25.906
some applicants write multiple grants, and it becomes a

492
00:29:25.946 --> 00:29:29.886
problem when some of these grants end up in the same study section, and

493
00:29:29.926 --> 00:29:32.566
it's always better to have the best idea put forward,

494
00:29:33.846 --> 00:29:37.416
so that you can focus on one. And it's okay to write a second idea.

495
00:29:37.486 --> 00:29:40.546
If you have a second idea, it's okay to write, but don't try to cram everything

496
00:29:40.586 --> 00:29:44.566
into a single cycle. And then if you have co-investigators

497
00:29:44.606 --> 00:29:48.586
in your application, it's always a good idea for them to read and provide feedback.

498
00:29:48.686 --> 00:29:52.556
Sometimes the letter of support or some of the information you are going

499
00:29:52.606 --> 00:29:54.526
to use using a co-investigator may

500
00:29:55.566 --> 00:29:56.146
have a fatal

501
00:29:57.026 --> 00:30:00.926
problem where one of you might have overlooked that

502
00:30:00.946 --> 00:30:04.826
problem. And it's always for new investigators, it's always good to have important

503
00:30:04.866 --> 00:30:08.066
manuscripts published so that reviewers have

504
00:30:09.366 --> 00:30:13.226
faith that what your hypothesis-driven research is,

505
00:30:13.346 --> 00:30:16.166
